["Clinical documentation reviewed in PowerChart, 79-year-old female with history of dementia  hyperlipidemia  and hypothyroidism who presented to the Emergency Department with a chief complaint of chest pain. \u00A0The patient's daughter  who was at bedside  reported that around 2100 last night  the patient was watching TV and began to look pale and ashy. \u00A0She reported symptoms like hot flashes and complained of left-sided chest discomfort. \u00A0The patient reported that this lasted briefly; however  occurred a few more times intermittently in the following hour. \u00A0The patient reported a development of cough during that time. \u00A0The patient's daughter added that the patient had eaten dinner normally and took her night medications before symptom onset., Initial laboratory workup revealed a troponin of 2.46. \u00A0Other lab work was essentially unremarkable. \u00A0EKG showed evidence of new left bundle-branch block as compared with last EKG in 2011. \u00A0The patient was tachycardic with a heart rate of 110. \u00A0In the Emergency Department  the patient developed dropping of oxygen saturation. \u00A0She was placed on BiPAP., CT chest showed no CT evidence of pulmonary embolus; however  marked bilateral bronchial wall thickening consistent with bronchitis  as well as pulmonary edema and mild trapping with moderate-sized bilateral pleural effusions. \u00A0The case was discussed with the cardiologist on call  who initiated IV heparin and optimization of patient's medical therapy. \u00A0The patient received IV Lasix and admitted to the Intensive Care Unit., 02/21/17 CARDIOLOGY NOTE, Acute non-ST segment elevation myocardial infarction: She has a left bundle branch block so we cannot be certain as to the territory of ischemia. I had a lengthy discussion with 2 daughters (daughter who is a veterinarian by phone) yesterday. I don't think she is a good candidate for invasive evaluation given her advanced dementia. My recommendations are for dual platelet therapy  beta blockers  high-dose atorvastatin  and ACE inhibitor. IF she were to have further chest pain or worsening heart failure could consider catheterization to see if something can be intervened upon but she would never be a surgical candidate. The other option would be for biventricular pacemaker-> she would never be an ICD candidate given the severity of her dementia. Will get up and ambulate today. \u00A0, Acute pulmonary edema: She has severe left ventricular dysfunction related to her left bundle branch block as well as underlying ischemic cardiomyopathy.
